 – Blynk Integration & Mobile Control Setup
🎯 Lesson Objective
In this lesson, students will learn:

How to fully set up the Blynk IoT platform
How to connect ESP32 with Blynk Cloud
How to design a mobile control dashboard
How to send commands from mobile to ESP32
By the end of this lesson, students will be able to control a robot using their smartphone over the internet.

📱 What is Blynk IoT?
Blynk is a powerful IoT platform that allows you to:

Control hardware remotely
Build mobile apps without coding
Communicate with ESP32 over the internet
👉 It works as a bridge between your mobile phone / pc and ESP32

🔄 How Blynk System Works
Mobile App/pc → Blynk Cloud → ESP32 → Robot

User presses a button in the app
Command goes to Blynk Cloud
ESP32 receives command via WiFi
Robot performs action

🛠️ COMPLETE BLYNK SETUP (STEP-BY-STEP)
      
🔹 Step 1 – Install App
   Download Blynk IoT from Play Store
  Open the app

🔹 Step 2 – Create Account
Sign up using email
Verify email
Login to dashboard

🔹 Step 3 – Create Template
Click on “Developer Zone”
Click “New Template”
Fill details:

Template Name → WiFi Robot
Hardware → ESP32
Connection Type → WiFi
👉 Click Create

🔹 Step 4 – Add Datastreams (VERY IMPORTANT)
Go to Datastreams → New Datastream → Virtual Pin

Create the following:

Name	  Virtual Pin       	 Type
Forward 	V0	         Integer
Backward	V1        	 Integer
Left	       V2	        Integer
Right   	V3	         Integer

👉 Set: ( because we get only 1 and 0 )
Min = 0
Max = 1

🔹 Step 5 – Create Device
Go to Devices
Click New Device
Select From Template
Choose your template
Click Create

🔹 Step 6 – Get Auth Token
Open your device
Copy Auth Token
👉 This will be used in ESP32 code

🔹 Step 7 – Create Mobile Dashboard
Open Blynk mobile app
Select your device
Click Edit Dashboard

🔹 Step 8 – Add Buttons
Add 4 Button Widgets:

Button 1:
Name: Forward
Datastream: V0
Mode: Switch
Button 2:
Name: Backward
Datastream: V1
Mode: Switch
Button 3:
Name: Left
Datastream: V2
Mode: Switch
Button 4:
Name: Right
Datastream: V3
Mode: Switch

🔹 Step 9 – Save Dashboard
Click Save

Exit edit mode
💻 ESP32 Code for Blynk Connection
 
#define BLYNK_TEMPLATE_ID “YourTemplateID”
#define BLYNK_TEMPLATE_NAME “WiFi Robot”
#define BLYNK_AUTH_TOKEN “YourAuthToken”
#include <WiFi.h>
#include <BlynkSimpleEsp32.h>

char ssid[] = “YourWiFiName”;
char pass[] = “YourPassword”;


 
🔍 Understanding Virtual Pins
Virtual Pins (V0, V1, etc.) are software pins
They send values from app to ESP32
Example:
Button ON → sends 1
Button OFF → sends 0



ESP32 connects to Blynk
Device status becomes Online
🧠 Key Learning Concepts
Cloud-based IoT control
Mobile app interface design
Virtual communication (no physical wires)
Real-time device interaction

⚠️ Common Issues & Solutions
Problem	Solution
Device Offline	Check WiFi connection
Wrong Auth Token	Copy correct token
Buttons not working	Check Virtual Pins
Not connecting to Blynk	Check internet

🔧 Troubleshooting Tips
Keep internet stable
Restart ESP32 if needed
Re-upload code if error occurs
Check Template ID and Auth Token carefully

